  Author                   = {Kathy S. Law},
  Journal                  = {Chemosphere - Global Change Science},
  Year                     = {1999},
  Number                   = {1-3},
  Pages                    = {19--31},
  Volume                   = {1},

  Abstract                 = {Trends in atmospheric carbon monoxide (CO) were positive until the late 1980s/early 1990s. Since then the global growth rate has been negative. In this paper, theoretical studies, investigating the causes for recent declining trends in CO, are reviewed. A variety of tools, ranging from numerical models to data analysis, have been used to further our understanding about the global distribution of CO and how its growth rate may be changing. Recent comparisons of results from chemistry-transport models (CTMs) with observations are used to illustrate how well current models perform. Regions of the atmosphere or times of year when specific features in the distribution are not well captured are highlighted. Models are also used to analyse the budget of CO. Uncertainties in the calculations are discussed. The main focus of this review is on hypotheses put forward to explain recent declining trends. These involve either changes in CO emissions or the major sink via reaction with the hydroxyl radical (OH). The extent to which proposed mechanisms can account for observed trends is explored.},
