@Article{Okkonen2011,
  Title                    = {A sequential modelling approach to assess groundwater–surface water resources in a snow dominated region of Finland},
  Author                   = {Jarkko Okkonen and Bjørn Kløve},
  Journal                  = {Journal of Hydrology},
  Year                     = {2011},
  Pages                    = {91-107},
  Volume                   = {411},

  Abstract                 = {Methodology was developed to estimate surface water–groundwater interactions in a changing climate
in cold, snow-dominated regions and tested on an unconfined esker aquifer in northern Finland. The
Watershed Simulation and Forecasting System (WSFS) model was used to simulate surface water levels.
A coupled heat and mass transfer model for soil–plant–atmosphere systems (CoupModel) was used to
simulate recharge. The CoupModel is able to simulate water flow through frozen soil. The simulated sur-
face water level and recharge data were linked to the Groundwater Modelling System (GMS) version 6.5,
and the three-dimensional groundwater flow model MODFLOW was used to study the impact of climate
variability on groundwater levels and groundwater–surface water interactions. In addition, under A1B
climate change scenario changes in aquifer storage and groundwater–surface water interactions were
studied through the end of the 21st century. Recharge was shown to be sensitive to changes in soil frost
and hence modelling approaches should include a soil frost component to account for the impact of frost
on hydraulic conductivity. Under A1B climate change scenario study, groundwater recharge is projected
to increase in winter months due to increase in snowmelt and decrease in soil frost depth. The spring
snowmelt peak in late spring will decrease. This will reduce aquifer storage in early spring, increasing
the vulnerability to summer droughts.},
  Doi                      = {10.1016/j.jhydrol.2011.09.038},
  File                     = {Okkonen2011.pdf:Okkonen2011.pdf:PDF},
  Groups                   = {Droughts},
  Owner                    = {claas},
  Review                   = {Idea/Topic
The paper investigates the influence of climate change on the groundwater-surface water resources (and the exchange between them), considering as a case study an equifer in a snow dominated region in northern Finland.

Data/Method 
Measurement data from the Pudasjärvi aquifer study site was used (e.g., groundwater levels between 1981 and 2000). Climate data from the AR4 was used for the A1B scenario as simulated by 19 general circulation models. Together with local observations, the delta-approach was used to assess climate change in the region.
The data was used together with a chain of three different models: one temperature and precipitation in the watershed, a 1-D model for coupled heat and mass transfer for soil-plant-atmosphere systems and one to simulate the groundwater flow.
One weakness of the method is the one-way approach (no influence of groundwater changes on surface water), which is argued to be reasonable in this specific region.
The models in the chain were not analyzed with respect to uncertainty.

Finding/Conclusion
The snowmelt period in spring is longer under climate change conditions and the snowmelt peak is shifted to earlier times in the year. Together with a greater annual recharge, the water potential of the aquifer is greater. A decrease in the amplitude of variation in surface water and groundwater levels are projected. Surface water infow to the aquifer is projected to occure more often.
Altogether, it is concluded that under A1B climate change scenario, groundwater discharge areas will be vulnerable to changes in groundwater-surface water exchange.

Evaluation
The study is quite interesting, but might be improved to be of general relevance. There are two main deficiencies: the missing uncertainty analysis of the different models in the model chain (and the resulting uncertainty of the entire chain) and the restriction to a one-way approach, which is not applicable in general to other regions.
The study serves as an example of what could happen to groundwater in the specific area.},
  Timestamp                = {2012.10.19}
}

